t620.text: Nursing is not easy; it is mentally, emotionally and physically taxing. I almost always need a time out after my shifts to recharge myself. Please don’t ever take nurses for granted. We really are angels in disguise . #nursing #weareangels

t621.text: The amount of times I’ve guided junior doctors, I’ve lost count... Anway, I could go on and on... but my point is this...

t622.text: We, as nurses are that front line for patients. We call the codes, we’re almost always the ones to initiate resuscitation; we check to make sure the doctors are doing the right thing, following policies etc.

t623.text: It is mentally taxing. I have to be switched on all the time, one mathematic misstep on a medication calculation could meaning permanently maiming or killing a patient. I have to be aware of a patient’s baseline at all times; to be able to pick up when a patient is deteriorating.

t624.text: The burnout rates among nurses and healthcare workers is astronomical. A study once found that the burnout rate of healthcare workers is on par with the military.

t625.text: It is gut wrenching to loose a patient... we as nurses, are there for all moments of life. You are also as a nurse, the frontline for abuse, be it verbal or physical from patients, family members etc.

t626.text: With their most precious person. You build such an emotional rapport that you, as a nurse almost become part of the family. The amount of times I’ve been called ‘Auntie’ by a set of parents . Compassion is a huge part of being a nurse. Death is also part of being a nurse...

t627.text: It is emotional; you are dealing with people in their most traumatic and vulnerable moments. You laugh with them, cry with them and comfort them. In my job as a NICU/SCN nurse, I am not just looking after newborns, I’m looking after the whole family... they trust me explicitly

t628.text: Nursing is incredibly physical; when I was a nurse working with adult patients; I use to have to lift and help move patients twice my size and weight. You are on your feet constantly... in one 12 and a half hour shift, I’m lucky to sit down for more than a couple of hours.

t629.text: Then once you graduate; you soon learn what shift work and a rotating roster is like; you give up weekends, public holidays and eventually much of your social life. You start to work night shifts. All this takes a massive toll on your body.

t630.text: I was doing a clinical placement WHILE undertaking my final exams for the semester. Meaning I was doing triple the amount of study.

t631.text: I really wish people would stop dismissing nursing as an ‘easy’ job. It is not. While your are studying a Bachelor of Nursing it is a round rotation of studying theory, doing clinical placements and practical exams as well as theory exams. I remember in my last semester...
